<treatment ID-GBIF-Taxon="182228162" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:30571CAEE3715A1DA7CE9B60FD267DD4" httpUri="http://treatment.plazi.org/id/30571CAEE3715A1DA7CE9B60FD267DD4" lastPageNumber="150" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">
<subSubSection pageId="149" pageNumber="150" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="149" pageNumber="150">
128. 
<taxonomicName LSID="30571CAE-E371-5A1D-A7CE-9B60FD267DD4" authority="Mozaff., Pakistan J. Bot. 34: 395, f. 2. 2002. (Mozaffarian 2002: 395)." authorityName="Mozaff., Pakistan J. Bot. 34: 395, f. 2. 2002. (Mozaffarian" authorityYear="2002" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus kurdistanicus" order="Solanales" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kurdistanicus">Convolvulus kurdistanicus Mozaff., Pakistan J. Bot. 34: 395, f. 2. 2002. (Mozaffarian 2002: 395).</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="149" pageNumber="150" type="type">
<paragraph pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="149" pageNumber="150">
IRAN, Kermanshah, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Mozaffarian</emphasis>
79475 (holotype TARI).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="149" pageNumber="150" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Perennial undershrub with woody taproot, from which arise many sericeous stems to 50 cm. Basal leaves unknown; stem leaves sessile, 20-40 cm long, linear-filiform. Flowers 3-5 in axillary and terminal dichasial cymes; bracteoles linear, acute; sepals 8 mm long (fide description) or 4-4.5 mm (fide illustration), ovate, mucronate, glabrous; corolla c. 1.8 cm long, white, midpetaline bands pubescent; ovary glabrous; style glabrous, much longer than stigmas (fide illustration). Capsule glabrous, 1-seeded.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="149" pageNumber="150" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="149" pageNumber="150">
Iran; Iraq (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Rawi</emphasis>
5720).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="149" pageNumber="150" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="149" pageNumber="150">
We have not seen the type material. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Rawi</emphasis>
5720 is annotated in the Kew herbarium as &quot; 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus leptocladus subsp. glabrisepalus" order="Solanales" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="leptocladus" subSpecies="glabrisepalus">Convolvulus leptocladus subsp. glabrisepalus</taxonomicName>
Kandemir&quot; and seems to fit perfectly with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mozaff., Pakistan J. Bot. 34: 395, f. 2. 2002. (Mozaffarian" authorityYear="2002" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus kurdistanicus" order="Solanales" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kurdistanicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Convolvulus kurdistanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as long as the sepals of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mozaff., Pakistan J. Bot. 34: 395, f. 2. 2002. (Mozaffarian" authorityYear="2002" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus kurdistanicus" order="Solanales" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kurdistanicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Convolvulus kurdistanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the more probable 4.5 mm long (as illustrated), rather than 8 mm long as described. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mozaff., Pakistan J. Bot. 34: 395, f. 2. 2002. (Mozaffarian" authorityYear="2002" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus kurdistanicus" order="Solanales" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kurdistanicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Convolvulus kurdistanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also extremely close to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bornm., Dan. Sci. Invest. Iran 4: 37. 1945. (Koeie" authorityYear="1945" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus koieanus" order="Solanales" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="koieanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Convolvulus koieanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differing only in the glabrous ovary. As 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mozaff., Pakistan J. Bot. 34: 395, f. 2. 2002. (Mozaffarian" authorityYear="2002" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus kurdistanicus" order="Solanales" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kurdistanicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Convolvulus kurdistanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bornm., Dan. Sci. Invest. Iran 4: 37. 1945. (Koeie" authorityYear="1945" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus koieanus" order="Solanales" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="koieanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Convolvulus koieanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
grow in neighbouring provinces of Iran, it seems quite possible that they will prove to beconspecific.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
